issue.title: Add a security policy
issue.body:
Hello 👋

I run a security community that finds and fixes vulnerabilities in OSS. A researcher (@jbonnett) has found a potential issue, which I would be eager to share with you.

Could you add a `SECURITY.md` file with an e-mail address for me to send further details to? GitHub [recommends](https://docs.github.com/en/code-security/getting-started/adding-a-security-policy-to-your-repository) a security policy to ensure issues are responsibly disclosed, and it would help direct researchers in the future.

Looking forward to hearing from you 👍

(cc @huntr-helper)

comment.body: Hey @jawnsy! Have you received our report from huntr.com?

issue.title: Argument of type "PrefectFuture[int, Sync]" cannot be assigned to parameter "i" of type "int" in function "__call__"

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: An improvement of an existing feature

labels.name: status:accepted
labels.description: We may work on this; we will accept work from external contributors

issue.body:
## Description

pyright error:
```
basic_flow.py:12:18 - error: Argument of type "PrefectFuture[int, Sync]" cannot be assigned to parameter "i" of type "int" in function "__call__"
    "PrefectFuture[int, Sync]" is incompatible with "int" (reportGeneralTypeIssues)
```

mypy error:
```
basic_flow.py:12: error: No overload variant of "__call__" of "Task" matches argument type "PrefectFuture[None, Literal[False]]"
basic_flow.py:12: note: Possible overload variants:
basic_flow.py:12: note:     def __call__(self, i: int) -> PrefectFuture[None, Literal[False]]
basic_flow.py:12: note:     def __call__(self, i: int) -> Awaitable[PrefectFuture[<nothing>, Literal[True]]]
```    

## Reproduction / Example

_basic_flow.py_:
```python
from prefect import flow, get_run_logger, task
from prefect.futures import PrefectFuture
from prefect.utilities.asyncio import Sync


@flow
def add_flow(i: int) -> PrefectFuture[int, Sync]:
    # result is PrefectFuture[int, Sync]
    result = add_one(i)

    # passing the result future will resolve to its int value
    print_result(result)    # <--- line 12: pyright/mypy errors here
    return result

@task
def add_one(i: int) -> int:
    return i + 1

@task
def print_result(i: int) -> None:
    logger = get_run_logger()
    logger.info(f"print_result: {i=}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    add_flow(1)

```

prefect 2.0b8

comment.body:
> Can you consider adding `cast_future` to the `prefect.futures`?

Or you can add a `cast` method to `PrefectFuture`.

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: An improvement of an existing feature

labels.name: status:accepted
labels.description: We may work on this; we will accept work from external contributors

issue.body:
## Description

pyright error:
```
basic_flow.py:12:18 - error: Argument of type "PrefectFuture[int, Sync]" cannot be assigned to parameter "i" of type "int" in function "__call__"
    "PrefectFuture[int, Sync]" is incompatible with "int" (reportGeneralTypeIssues)
```

mypy error:
```
basic_flow.py:12: error: No overload variant of "__call__" of "Task" matches argument type "PrefectFuture[None, Literal[False]]"
basic_flow.py:12: note: Possible overload variants:
basic_flow.py:12: note:     def __call__(self, i: int) -> PrefectFuture[None, Literal[False]]
basic_flow.py:12: note:     def __call__(self, i: int) -> Awaitable[PrefectFuture[<nothing>, Literal[True]]]
```    

## Reproduction / Example

_basic_flow.py_:
```python
from prefect import flow, get_run_logger, task
from prefect.futures import PrefectFuture
from prefect.utilities.asyncio import Sync


@flow
def add_flow(i: int) -> PrefectFuture[int, Sync]:
    # result is PrefectFuture[int, Sync]
    result = add_one(i)

    # passing the result future will resolve to its int value
    print_result(result)    # <--- line 12: pyright/mypy errors here
    return result

@task
def add_one(i: int) -> int:
    return i + 1

@task
def print_result(i: int) -> None:
    logger = get_run_logger()
    logger.info(f"print_result: {i=}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    add_flow(1)

```

prefect 2.0b8

comment.body:
Hi! Here is my workaround:

```python
from typing import TypeVar, cast

from prefect.futures import PrefectFuture
from prefect.utilities.asyncutils import A


T = TypeVar("T")

def cast_future(val: PrefectFuture[T, A]) -> T:
    return cast(T, val)
```

Then the original code can be rewritten like this:

```python
from prefect import flow, get_run_logger, task
from prefect.futures import PrefectFuture
from prefect.utilities.asyncutils import Sync


@flow
def add_flow(i: int) -> PrefectFuture[int, Sync]:
    # result is PrefectFuture[int, Sync]
    result = add_one.submit(i)

    # passing the result future will resolve to its int value
    print_result.submit(cast_future(result))  # cast_future casts to int
    return result

@task
def add_one(i: int) -> int:
    return i + 1

@task
def print_result(i: int) -> None:
    logger = get_run_logger()
    logger.info(f"print_result: {i=}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    add_flow(1)
```

Why it's better than just `typing.cast`:

1. With `typing.cast`, you can cast to any type. It increases the probability of making a mistake.
2. With `cast_future`, the type is detected automatically.

Can you consider adding `cast_future` to the `prefect.futures`?

issue.title: Keep server deployment property if deployment already exists and property is omitted from `prefect deploy`

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: An improvement of an existing feature

labels.name: needs:triage
labels.description: Needs feedback from the Prefect product team

issue.body:
### First check

- [X] I added a descriptive title to this issue.
- [X] I used the GitHub search to find a similar request and didn't find it.
- [X] I searched the Prefect documentation for this feature.

### Prefect Version

2.x

### Describe the current behavior

Right now, if you have a deployment definition stored in `prefect.yaml` that does not contain values for properties such as `schedule`, a null (empty) schedule gets pushed to the server, overriding any schedule that was set up in the UI for that deployment previously. 

### Describe the proposed behavior

If a property is omitted from the deployment definition, such as `schedule`, it should assume that it keeps whatever is on the server currently if the deployment already exists. It should not override a schedule that was set through the UI with an empty (null) schedule. This behavior should also apply for any other property, such as `description`, or `tags`.

### Example Use

```
- name: My-First-Deployment
  version: null
  tags:
  - finance
  description: Generates multiple CSVs for the finance department
  entrypoint: flows\Finance\my_csv_generator.py.py:generate_csvs
```

In the above example of a deployment definition in `prefect.yaml`, if `My-First-Deployment` deployment already exists in the server, and you run `prefect deploy -n My-First-Deployment`, the CLI asks: 

`? Would you like to configure a schedule for this deployment? [y/n] (y): `

It should not ask this, since you purposely did not include a `schedule`, because it was already set through the UI. If you select `n` as a response, it creates an empty schedule property ( `schedule: ` ) and whatever schedule was in the server gets overriden with no schedule at all. 

### Additional context

I assume this behavior should also apply to the normal parameters you pass to `prefect deploy` via the CLI, not just the ones set in `prefect.yaml`.

issue.title: Multiprocessing deadlock
issue.body:
### First check

- [X] I added a descriptive title to this issue.
- [X] I used the GitHub search to find a similar issue and didn't find it.
- [X] I searched the Prefect documentation for this issue.
- [X] I checked that this issue is related to Prefect and not one of its dependencies.

### Bug summary

Running native python `multiprocessing` with more than 1 worker leads to a deadlock at the `.join()` step.  I am running this in a docker container.



### Reproduction

```python3
Inside a docker container:


import multiprocessing as mp

def mp_task(args):
    return 1

@flow 
def mp_flow():
    n_cpu = mp.cpu_count()
    pool = multiprocessing.Pool(processes=n_cpu)
    args = iter([1,2,3])

    res = pool.starmap(mp_task, args)
    pool.close()
    pool.join()
    return res
```


### Error

None, just 0 progress.

I will get full core utility across all cpus and then they just drop to 0. and no progress is made.


### Versions

```Text
prefect 2.13
```


### Additional context

_No response_

comment.body:
> 获取此问题的详细信息和 MRE 会很有帮助。我仍然无法使用我自己的示例进行重现：
> 
> ```python
> # Python 3.8.17
> import multiprocessing as mp
> 
> from prefect import flow
> 
> 
> def mp_task(*args):
>     print("hi", args)
>     return 1
> 
> 
> @flow
> def mp_flow():
>     n_cpu = mp.cpu_count()
>     print(n_cpu)
>     pool = mp.Pool(processes=n_cpu)
> 
>     res = pool.starmap(mp_task, [[1, 2], [2, 2]])
>     pool.close()
>     pool.join()
>     return res
> 
> 
> if __name__ == "__main__":
>     mp_flow()
> ```

```
# Python 3.8.17
import multiprocessing as mp

from prefect import flow, get_run_logger


def mp_task(*args):
    print("hi", args)
    return 1


@flow
def mp_flow():
    # logger will block
    logger = get_run_logger()
    n_cpu = mp.cpu_count()
    logger.info(n_cpu)
    pool = mp.Pool(processes=n_cpu)

    res = pool.starmap(mp_task, [[1, 2], [2, 2]])
    pool.close()
    pool.join()
    return res


if __name__ == '__main__':
    mp_flow()

```

issue.title: env variables are not set on job

labels.name: needs:triage
labels.description: Needs feedback from the Prefect product team

issue.body:
### First check

- [X] I added a descriptive title to this issue.
- [X] I used the GitHub search to find a similar issue and didn't find it.
- [X] I searched the Prefect documentation for this issue.
- [X] I checked that this issue is related to Prefect and not one of its dependencies.

### Bug summary

Environment variables are not coming up as expected in google cloud run - push work pools. We have set up env variables in work pool config which is not reflected back in the flow run when deploying using prefect.yaml but works with .deploy() method. 

- With deploy method from flow code - work pool env variables are reflected back in the flow
- With deployment yaml block style deployment- work pool env variables aren't reflected back into the flow but env variables defined in prefect.yaml works.


### Reproduction

```python3
set up enviornment variable in google cloud run- push workpool config
deploy flow to read env variable using `prefect deploy' command to the workpool
```


### Error

```python3
print(os.environ["TEST"])
  File "/opt/homebrew/Cellar/python@3.10/3.10.9/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.10/lib/python3.10/os.py", line 680, in __getitem__
    raise KeyError(key) from None
KeyError: 'TEST'
```


### Versions

```Text
2.13.8
```


### Additional context


Not sure how the precedence of env variables works when we can define it in multiple places - prefect.yaml, workpool config

issue.title: PREFECT_API_KEY exposed when using service account with google cloud run - push workpool

labels.name: needs:triage
labels.description: Needs feedback from the Prefect product team

issue.body:
### First check

- [X] I added a descriptive title to this issue.
- [X] I used the GitHub search to find a similar issue and didn't find it.
- [X] I searched the Prefect documentation for this issue.
- [X] I checked that this issue is related to Prefect and not one of its dependencies.

### Bug summary

With Google Cloud run- push work pool using service account, the PREFECT_API_KEY variable needs to be passed as an environment variable and is exposed as plain text in google cloud run job configuration.
This is a security concern.


Tested the same approach using private prefect account and google cloud run-push workpool, didn't have to pass PREFECT_API_KEY and flow worked. Google cloud run job configuration has PREFECT_API_KEY environment variable which may be a JWT token.
When moved to enterprise prefect account, this didn't work out. And needed to pass in PREFECT_API_KEY as env variable through deployment yaml/workpool config,which gets exposed in cloud run job configuration as plain text.

If we do not pass in PREFECT_API_KEY we get the below error
> raise PrefectHTTPStatusError.from_httpx_error(exc) from exc.__cause__
prefect.exceptions.PrefectHTTPStatusError: Client error '403 Forbidden' for url 'https://api.prefect.cloud/api/accounts/xxxxxxx/workspaces/xxxxxxx/flow_runs/74275246-6328-464f-882f-925a6eb63406'

> Response: {'detail': {'reauth_needed': '7c41debb-fb39-4e40-97c0-846f9f1b9e93'}}

### Reproduction

```python3
snippet of deployment yaml below

deployments:
- name: dv-fetch
  version:
  tags: []
  description:
  entrypoint: flow.py:dv_fetch
  parameters: {}
  work_pool:
    name: gcr-dv
    work_queue_name:
    job_variables:
      image: '{{ build-image.image }}'
      env:
        PREFECT_API_KEY: xxxxxx
      service_account_name: yyyy@xxxx.iam.gserviceaccount.com
  schedule:
  build:
  - prefect_docker.deployments.steps.build_docker_image:
      requires: prefect-docker>=0.3.1
      id: build-image
      dockerfile: Dockerfile
      image_name:
        australia-southeast1-docker.pkg.dev/vcdi-np-svc/vcdi-dv/prefect2/dv-fetch
      tag: latest
      platform: amd64
  push:
  - prefect_docker.deployments.steps.push_docker_image:
      requires: prefect-docker>=0.3.1
      image_name: '{{ build-image.image_name }}'
      tag: '{{ build-image.tag }}'
```


### Error

_No response_

### Versions

```Text
2.x
```


### Additional context

_No response_

- Share an example to help us understand the change in user experience.

Happy engineering!

Share an example of the change in action.

A code blurb is best. Changes to features should include an example that is executable by a new user.
